{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"df573c01-1cea-4317-83be-b7df143b6427","content":"There's no workflow file in the current directory, so here's the general guidance for switching to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC):\n\n### 1. Configure NuGet.org\n- Go to **nuget.org → Manage Packages → Trusted Publishers**\n- Add a new trusted publisher policy linking your GitHub repository (owner, repo, optionally branch/environment)\n\n### 2. Update your GitHub Actions workflow\n\n**Remove:**\n```yaml\n- run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }} --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Add/change:**\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # Required for OIDC token\n  contents: read\n\nsteps:\n  - name: Push to NuGet (trusted publishing)\n    run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n    env:\n      NUGET_AUTH_TOKEN: \"\"  # not needed with trusted publishing\n```\n\nThe key steps:\n1. **Grant `id-token: write`** permission so the runner can request an OIDC JWT.\n2. **Remove `--api-key`** — the `dotnet nuget push` command will automatically use the OIDC token when no API key is provided and trusted publishing is configured.\n3. **Delete the `NUGET_API_KEY` secret** from your repo settings once verified.\n\n### 3. (Optional) Use an environment\nFor extra security, scope the trusted publisher to a GitHub **environment** (e.g., `production`) and require approvals:\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  publish:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    environment: production\n    permissions:\n      id-token: write\n      contents: read\n```\n\n> **Note:** NuGet trusted publishing is relatively new. Check [NuGet's trusted publishing docs](https://learn.microsoft.com/nuget/nuget-org/trusted-publishing) for the latest setup steps, as the nuget.org UI and `dotnet` CLI support may have evolved.\n\nWant me to create a sample workflow file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8fd6ef08-0359-42a4-aefa-303eef18fe20","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory appears to be empty. The user is asking a general question about switching from NuGet API key-based publishing to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC) in GitHub Actions. I don't have their workflow file to look at, so I'll provide guidance based on what NuGet trusted publishing requires.","outputTokens":596,"requestId":"6C42:1F8B8F:D78B85:10BBB21:6A0129C5"},"id":"3d5136aa-5a2d-417a-99b7-a6a835aacc62","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:58:57.998Z","parentId":"3ce17b1f-13d1-411f-83eb-097f9cba5760"}
